		 Monday, June 28, 2004  Nation at a Glance				 																J amp;K bans outsiders from rail work sites				 																																																	Jammu (PTI): Entry of outsiders to the construction sites of Jammu-Udhampur-Baramulla railway project has been banned from Sunday and prohibitory orders imposed near them following the abduction and murder of an Ircon engineer and his brother by militants.				 																																																										Sohan Lal Raina, the additional district magistrate for Ramban, under which all the present construction sites fall, said the ban would remain in force for two months.				 																																																										The superintendent of Ramban police has been instructed to strictly impose the prohibitory orders, Raina added. All the railway construction sites have been made out of bound for outsiders and locals.				 																																																										Only workers and officers of the executing agencies will be allowed at the sites. Tunnelling and other work of the railway project stretching from Udhampur to Anantnag is being carried out by Ircon and other agencies.				 																																																										Raina said construction work is under progress in Bunkote, Krawah, Kaskoot, Gund Adalkote, Jagirnamdar, Hagazine Asher, Darshipura, Chreel, Lumbar bridge and four railways stations.				 																																																										Ircon engineer Sudhir Kumar Pundir and his brother Sandeep were abducted for ransom by militants from Awantipora in Pulwama district on Wednesday and their soaked bodies were found with the throats slit in a cornfield two days later.				 																Blow to Kanishka witnessesVancouver (PTI): In a ruling that could have a bearing on the ongoing Air-India bombing trial, Canadas apex court has held that reluctant witnesses can now be forced to testify at investigative hearings under the countrys new anti-terrorism laws.				 																																																										At a secret hearing of the Air-India trial, the government and police have been trying to compel an uncooperative witness, who cannot be named under a publication ban, to answer questions related to the 1985 Kanishka bombing. 				 																																																										The case relates to two Canadian men  Ripudaman Singh Malik and Ajaib Singh Bagri, key accused in the planting of a bomb on the Kanishka flight which crashed off the coast of Ireland in June, 1985, killing all 329 people on board. 				 																																																										The witness has so far refused to testify, arguing that the laws violate Canadas charter of rights but in a six to three decision last week, the countrys Supreme Court ruled that the law is fair and that witnesses can be forced to help police investigations in cases related to national security. 				 																																																										It said the witness should testify in open and that such hearings do not violate the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, Canadian daily The Globe and Mail said. 				 																																																										Prosecutors at the Air-India trial had so far wanted the whole process kept secret and went to some lengths last year to bar journalists from the proceedings.				 																HC reprieve for errant porters				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): Two porters, whose licences had been revoked by the railways in 2000 for illegally selling seats in unreserved compartments, have been granted relief on humanitarian grounds by Delhi High Court. The court has directed the railway authorities to consider their appeal for restoring licences.				 																																																										Justice Manmohan Sarin passed the order saying revocation of license was a harsh punishment as it robbed petitioner Babu Lal and another porter of their only means of livelihood.				 																Arrest warrant				 																																																	Muzaffarnagar (PTI): An arrest warrant has been issued against Bhartiya Kisan Union leader Mahender Singh Tikaits son Naresh in connection with a murder case. Naresh and two others have been accused of the murder of Jagbir Singh on September 6 last year. 				 																Rao infection				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): Former Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Raos discharge from the hospital has been delayed following a chest infection. An official of the All India Institute of Medical Sciences said: Rao is suffering from chest infection from the last two days. It is due to the weather change and he is responding to the treatment. Rao was admitted in AIIMS on June 16.				 																3 die of poisoning				 																																																	Muzaffarnagar (PTI): Three children of a family were killed after consuming poisonous prasad distributed by some miscreants at Rampur village. Police said eight-year-old Satyam, four-year-old Shivam and their sister Ammu, 11, went to get food for their father, who was working in the fields, when the poisonous prasad was given to them.				 																Drugs seized				 																																																	Hyderabad (PTI): Customs officials seized a huge cache of narcotic drugs at Rajiv Gandhi International Airport on Sunday. Officials said one person who was about to board a flight to Dubai with the contraband was taken into custody and interrogated at the airport.				 																Graft arrest				 																																																	Jaipur (PTI): A revenue officer has been arrested for allegedly accepting a bribe of Rs 3,000. 																		The Shiromani Gurdwara Prabandhak Committee plans to introduce gold and silver coins to celebrate the 400th Parkash Utsav of the Guru Granth Sahib. The coins would be engraved the committees seal on one side and the Golden Temple on the other.
